<div class="note-box">
  <p><strong>The one thing that makes or breaks this edit:</strong> the footage has to feel like a life being lived, not a highlight reel being performed. Every clip should look like it was captured in the middle of something real — not set up for the camera.</p>
</div>

<div class="divider"></div>
<div class="section-label">Editing Notes</div>

<div class="shot" data-id="edit1">
  <div class="shot-header" onclick="toggle(this.parentElement)">
    <div class="cb"><svg class="check-icon" viewBox="0 0 13 13"><polyline points="2,6.5 5.5,10 11,3"/></svg></div>
    <div class="shot-body">
      <div class="shot-num">Edit</div>
      <div class="shot-title">Text overlay — every voiceover line on screen</div>
      <div class="shot-detail">Each line appears as the voice delivers it. One line at a time. Clean minimal font, white or off-white. Never two lines simultaneously. The text IS the hook for muted viewers.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="shot" data-id="edit2">
  <div class="shot-header" onclick="toggle(this.parentElement)">
    <div class="cb"><svg class="check-icon" viewBox="0 0 13 13"><polyline points="2,6.5 5.5,10 11,3"/></svg></div>
    <div class="shot-body">
      <div class="shot-num">Edit</div>
      <div class="shot-title">Pacing — cut to the rhythm of the words</div>
      <div class="shot-detail">Each clip change should land on a new line of voiceover. The listicle format means fast cuts are expected — don't hold a clip past its line. "That's a compliment" gets its own still moment.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="shot" data-id="edit3">
  <div class="shot-header" onclick="toggle(this.parentElement)">
    <div class="cb"><svg class="check-icon" viewBox="0 0 13 13"><polyline points="2,6.5 5.5,10 11,3"/></svg></div>
    <div class="shot-body">
